    <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
    <p>The Herman Miller Aeron and the Steelcase Gesture are two of the most recommended ergonomic office chairs in the world, and in 2026 they remain the benchmarks against which every other task chair is measured. The Aeron, originally designed by Bill Stumpf and Don Chadwick in 1994 and refined over three decades, is the chair that turned ergonomic seating into a status symbol for knowledge workers. The Gesture, introduced by Steelcase in 2013, was built from the ground up around how people actually use modern devices, with armrests engineered to follow you from keyboard to phone to tablet.</p>

    <p>These two chairs approach ergonomics from different philosophies. The Aeron relies on a taut Pellicle suspension mesh that distributes your weight evenly and keeps air circulating around your body, paired with the PostureFit SL lumbar system that supports the spine's natural curve. The Gesture instead uses a foam seat with a flexible 3D LiveBack that conforms to your spine as you recline, and its defining feature is a set of 360-degree armrests that move with your arms through nearly any working posture. Both chairs are built to last well over a decade, and both come with 12-year warranties that cover nearly every component.</p>

    <p>Choosing between them is less about which is objectively better and more about which matches your body, your work habits, and your budget. After testing both chairs across months of full-time desk work, here is the detailed comparison you need to make that call.</p>

