      <li>✗ Fabric and foam trap more heat than the Aeron's mesh</li>
      <li>✗ Single size means fit is less precise for very small or tall users</li>
      <li>✗ Lumbar support is less targeted than the Aeron's PostureFit SL</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="performance">Performance</h2>
    <p>In day-to-day comfort, the two chairs diverge based on how you sit and what you value. The Aeron's Pellicle mesh is its defining performance feature. Because the seat is a suspended membrane rather than a foam pad, your weight is distributed across the entire contact area, which eliminates the pressure points that build up under your sit bones on a conventional chair. For people who run warm or who work in environments without strong air conditioning, the mesh's breathability is a genuine quality-of-life improvement, keeping your back and legs noticeably cooler across an eight-hour day. The trade-off is firmness: the Aeron does not have the plush, sinking-in feel that foam lovers expect, and some users need a few weeks to adjust to the sensation.</p>

    <p>The Gesture's performance strength is adaptability. Its 3D LiveBack is a matrix of flexible connectors that move independently with your spine, so when you recline to think, lean forward to type, or twist to reach for a mouse, the back stays in contact with you rather than forcing you back into a single fixed position. The 360-degree armrests are the standout feature and the main reason many people choose the Gesture: they adjust in height, width, pivot, and rotation, meaning you can set them to support your arms while typing, then rotate them inward to support your forearms while holding a phone, or flip them back entirely when you want to sit cross-legged. For people who work across multiple devices and shift posture constantly, this flexibility is unmatched.</p>

    <p>For lower-back pain specifically, the Aeron with PostureFit SL has the edge. PostureFit SL uses two adjustable pads that press against the lower back to stabilize the pelvis and maintain the spine's natural curve, which is particularly effective for people who suffer from lumbar fatigue after long sitting sessions. The Gesture's lumbar support is adjustable and competent, but it is less targeted than the Aeron's dedicated PostureFit system. If back pain is your primary concern, the Aeron is the safer bet; if device-switching and posture variety define your workday, the Gesture is the better tool.</p>

    <h2 id="price">Price</h2>
    <p>The Aeron starts at $1,495 for the standard configuration with PostureFit SL, and upgrading to the fully loaded version with adjustable arms and a polished aluminum base can push the price toward $1,800. The Gesture starts at $979 and reaches roughly $1,300 in its top configuration. That means the Gesture typically costs $500 less than a comparable Aeron, which is a meaningful difference when outfitting a home office or an entire team.</p>

    <p>However, both chairs should be evaluated on a cost-per-year basis rather than sticker price alone. With 12-year warranties and construction designed to last well beyond that, either chair works out to roughly $80–$125 per year of use, which is competitive with chairs that cost a third as much but need replacing every few years. The Aeron also holds its resale value exceptionally well, often retaining 40–60% of its purchase price on the used market after several years, which partly offsets its higher initial cost. For most buyers, the Gesture's lower price makes it the stronger value, while the Aeron's long-term durability and resale value narrow the gap over time.</p>

    <h2 id="who-wins">Who Wins</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>For back pain and posture support:</strong> Herman Miller Aeron wins because the PostureFit SL system provides the most targeted lumbar support of any task chair, stabilizing the pelvis and supporting the spine's natural curve.</li>
      <li><strong>For multi-device work and posture variety:</strong> Steelcase Gesture wins because its 360-degree armrests and flexible LiveBack adapt to every position, from keyboard typing to phone holding to reclined reading.</li>
      <li><strong>For warm climates and breathability:</strong> Herman Miller Aeron wins because the full Pellicle mesh seat and back keep air circulating, preventing the heat buildup that foam seats cause during long sessions.</li>
      <li><strong>For budget and value:</strong> Steelcase Gesture wins because it delivers comparable ergonomics and the same 12-year warranty for roughly $500 less than the Aeron.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="recommendation">Final Recommendation</h2>
    <p>If you want the most refined, breathable, and iconic ergonomic chair available and your budget allows, the Herman Miller Aeron is our top pick. Its PostureFit SL lumbar support, three-size fit system, and Pellicle mesh make it the gold standard for people who sit for long hours and prioritize spinal health and temperature regulation. It costs more, but its 12-year warranty and exceptional resale value make it a justifiable long-term investment for anyone who treats their chair as essential infrastructure.</p>

    <p>If you work across multiple devices, shift postures constantly, or simply want excellent ergonomics without spending $1,500, the Steelcase Gesture is the smarter choice. Its 360-degree armrests are genuinely unmatched, its LiveBack adapts to your spine as you move, and its foam seat is more forgiving for users who find mesh too firm. At $979, it delivers about 90% of the Aeron's benefits at roughly two-thirds of the price, making it the best value in the premium ergonomic chair category.</p>

    <p>The simplest way to decide: choose the Aeron if you prioritize breathability, targeted lumbar support, and precise sizing; choose the Gesture if you prioritize armrest flexibility, cushioned comfort, and value. Both are chairs you will likely still be using a decade from now.</p>
